element.documentation:
"A lot of excess admin time is spent on checking if data transfer has happened.
All in all, it is an inefficient work flow creating extra work load in the back office (for the Bid Scenario Planner but also for Pricing Specialists within Sales who needs to update these data during Value Engineering phase), and it is also presenting a risk of entering wrong data into SAP Project Builder."

"If we do not show the consequence of changes to the schedule in ""real time"" then we have a hard time delivering forecasts with sufficient quality to Finance who is requesting monthly ToR forecasting.
It could also have an effect for a Site Manager who cannot see what amount of contingency has been calculated into the project schedule which affects their ability to plan tasks on site and order tools etc. with more accuracy and understanding of LDs. "

"This creates inaccurate payment schedules (close to 80% of the cash-in comes from deliverables around Manufacturing) and the times when we can invoice the Customer is very important to secure a consistent and stable cash flow.
It also affects our ability to mitigate risks for our construction project execution if we do not get the correct timings from Manufacturing (i.e. secure more resources for pre-installation to mitigate on delays deriving from Manufacturing)"

"This creates a lot of additional admin time, with no realized benefits, spent by Project Planners on updating systems because data does not flow automatically between SAP / O9 / Primavera
"

"This affects our project schedule because it will be unprecise - either if transport are happening before or after original planned dates. This ultimately affects our sites' ability to plan and prepare on site because the arrival of components drive all execution work"

"It affects our ability to: (1) understand how the progress affects project schedule, (2) report on project aspects that i.e. has to do with financial forecasts (3) retrieve info on when we have reached milestones "

"The pain point is that we end up with ""dead data"" and loss of system interfacing affecting the output for: (1) Site Managers who need to create a Site Schedule (2) Reporting purposes where we cannot pull out data from P6 / SAP (3) The quality of our ability to forecast demands"

"The pain point is that we end up with ""dead data"" and loss of system interfacing affecting the output for: (1) Site Managers who need to create a Site Schedule (2) Reporting purposes where we cannot pull out data from P6 / SAP (3) The quality of our ability to forecast demands"
This is still "new land" for us where we will have to obtain an overview of all new features before we decide on how to adapt and how we might need to train users
The pain point is that because of the lack of accuracy, users lose trust in the system.

"This affects the quality of the data used for reporting purposes across the organisation.
"

As mentioned in some other challenge, in LAT the TOR fcst is managed by PMO with manual inputs in SAP and breaking the link with P6. Also the project control is done with other tools (Ms-Project, Excel sheets).
The flow of approval for having the IDP changed takes approx. 2 weeks, so it is hard to rely on short-term dates being correct.

"Every project planner then spends signifant admin time to transfer these data manually from Excel to P6. This curently has to be done twice a month where all 10 Planners spend almost 1 week to process all these manual data transfers"
